these cervical cytology findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CIN I","CIN II","CIN III","Invasive squamous cell carcinoma","Normal cervical epithelium"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description represents \u003Cstrong\u003ECIN II\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by moderate dysplasia affecting the lower two-thirds of the epithelial thickness. Nuclear abnormalities include enlargement, hyperchromasia, and irregular chromatin distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECIN I\u003C/strong\u003E shows mild dysplasia limited to the lower third of the epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003ECIN III\u003C/strong\u003E involves severe dysplasia or carcinoma in situ affecting the full thickness of the epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003EInvasive squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows breach of the basement membrane. \u003Cstrong\u003ENormal cervical epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates orderly maturation with regular nuclear features and maintained cellular polarity throughout all layers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CIN classification system has three grades (I-III) that reflect the proportion of epithelium showing dysplastic changes. This helps guide clinical management and predicts risk of progression to invasive disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN) II shows moderate dysplasia with abnormal cells in the lower 2/3 of the epithelium","CIN classification ranges from I (mild) to III (severe), with no CIN IV category","Cytological changes in CIN II include nuclear enlargement, hyperchromasia, and irregular chromatin distribution"],"references":["\u0022Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (3) CIN2\u0022 by KGH is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Cervical_intraepithelial_neoplasia_(3)_CIN2.jpg","Pangarkar MA. The Bethesda System for reporting cervical cytology. Cytojournal. 2022 Apr 30;19:28. doi: 10.25259/CMAS_03_07_2021. PMID: 35673697; PMCID: PMC9168399","Bal MS, Goyal R, Suri AK, Mohi MK. Detection of abnormal cervical cytology in Papanicolaou smears. J Cytol. 2012 Jan;29(1):45-7. doi: 10.4103/0970-9371.93222. PMID: 22438616; PMCID: PMC3307451","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57508"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21194"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21194"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DJ4sqyAWRPdYwAcELmj9bD5kmWzlVt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DJ4sqyAWRPdYwAcELmj9bD5kmWzlVt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":700,"height":527}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57508"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:31:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:32:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8542"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72040"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms